<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-basic-properties"
  xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Basic Properties</title>

  <introduction>
    <p>
      The definition of continuity is local and quantitative, but in practice
      it is often convenient to test continuity using sequences. Once that
      criterion is available, several basic permanence properties follow
      immediately: sums, products, quotients, and compositions of continuous
      functions are again continuous. These results will let us build large
      classes of examples from a small stock of simple continuous functions.
    </p>
  </introduction>

  <subsection xml:id="subsec-sequential-characterization-of-continuity">
    <title>Sequential Characterization</title>

    <p>
      The following criterion replaces the <m>\varepsilon</m>-<m>\delta</m>
      definition with a statement about images of convergent sequences. It is
      often the most efficient way to prove that a function is continuous.
    </p>

    <proposition xml:id="prop-sequential-characterization-of-continuity">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>S \subseteq \R</m>, let <m>f \colon S \to \R</m>, and let
          <m>c \in S</m>. Then <m>f</m> is continuous at <m>c</m> if and only
          if for every sequence <m>(x_n)</m> in <m>S</m> with
          <m>x_n \to c</m>, we have
          <md>f(x_n) \to f(c).</md>
        </p>
      </statement>

      <proof>
        <p>
          First suppose that <m>f</m> is continuous at <m>c</m>, and let
          <m>(x_n)</m> be a sequence in <m>S</m> such that <m>x_n \to c</m>.
          Let <m>\varepsilon \gt 0</m> be given. By continuity at <m>c</m>,
          there exists <m>\delta \gt 0</m> such that <m>|f(x)-f(c)|
          \lt \varepsilon</m> whenever <m>x \in S</m> and <m>|x-c| \lt
          \delta</m>. Since <m>x_n \to c</m>, <m>|x_n-c| \lt \delta</m>
          for all but finitely many <m>n</m>. Hence <m>|f(x_n)-f(c)| \lt
          \varepsilon</m> for all but finitely many <m>n</m>, so <m>f(x_n)
          \to f(c)</m>.
        </p>

	<p>
	   Conversely, assume <m>f(x_n) \to f(c)</m> for every sequence
	   <m>(x_n)</m> in <m>S</m> that converges to <m>c</m> but <m>f</m>
	   is not continuous at <m>c</m>. Then there exists <m>\varepsilon_0
	   \gt 0</m> such that for every <m>n \in \N</m> there exists
	   <m>x_n \in S</m> with <m>|x_n-c| \lt 1/n</m> and

          <md>|f(x_n)-f(c)| \ge \varepsilon_0.</md>
          
	  Clearly, <m>x_n \to c</m>, but <m>f(x_n)</m> does not converge
	  to <m>f(c)</m>, contradicting the hypothesis. Therefore <m>f</m>
	  must be continuous at <m>c</m>.
	</p>
      </proof>
    </proposition>

    <p>
      We will use this <term>sequential characterization of
      continuity</term><idx>sequential characterization of continuity</idx>
      repeatedly. Once continuity is translated into a statement about
      convergent sequences, the usual algebraic properties of limits give
      the corresponding algebraic properties of continuous functions.
    </p>

  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="subsec-algebra-of-continuous-functions">
    <title>Algebra of Continuous Functions</title>

    <proposition xml:id="prop-algebra-of-continuous-functions">
      <statement>
	<p>
	  Let <m>f,g \colon S \to \R</m> be continuous at <m>c \in S</m>, then
	  so are <m>f+g</m> and <m>fg</m>.  Moreover, if <m>g(c) \neq 0</m>,
	  then <m>1/g</m> and hence <m>f/g</m> are also continuous at <m>c</m>.
	</p>
      </statement>

      <proof>
        <p>
          Pick a sequence <m>(x_n)</m> in <m>S</m> that converges to <m>c</m>.
          Since <m>f</m> and <m>g</m> are continuous at <m>c</m>, the
          sequential characterization gives
          <md>f(x_n) \to f(c)
            \quad\text{and}\quad g(x_n) \to g(c).
          </md>
          Therefore <xref ref="prop-limit-laws-sequences"/> implies that
          <md>(f+g)(x_n)=f(x_n)+g(x_n) \to f(c)+g(c)=(f+g)(c)</md>
          and
          <md>(fg)(x_n)=f(x_n)g(x_n) \to f(c)g(c)=(fg)(c).</md>
          Hence <m>f+g</m> and <m>fg</m> are continuous at <m>c</m>.
        </p>

        <p>
          Now assume <m>g(c) \neq 0</m>. Since <m>g(x_n) \to g(c)</m>, we
          have <m>g(x_n) \neq 0</m> for all sufficiently large <m>n</m>. Thus,
          by dropping finitely many terms if necessary, we may assume
          <m>g(x_n) \neq 0</m> for all <m>n</m>. Then the reciprocal part of
          <xref ref="prop-limit-laws-sequences"/> gives
          <md>\frac{1}{g(x_n)} \to \frac{1}{g(c)}.</md>
          Thus <m>1/g</m> is continuous at <m>c</m> by the sequential
          characterization of continuity. Applying the product result to
          <m>f</m> and <m>1/g</m>, we conclude that <m>f/g=f(1/g)</m> is
          continuous at <m>c</m>.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </proposition>

    <proposition xml:id="prop-composition-preserves-continuity">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>S,T \subseteq \R</m>, let <m>f \colon S \to T</m>, and let
          <m>g \colon T \to \R</m>. If <m>f</m> is continuous at
          <m>c \in S</m> and <m>g</m> is continuous at <m>f(c)</m>, then the
          composition <m>g \circ f</m> is continuous at <m>c</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>

      <proof>
        <p>
          Let <m>(x_n)</m> be a sequence in <m>S</m> with <m>x_n \to c</m>.
          Since <m>f</m> is continuous at <m>c</m>, we have
          <m>f(x_n) \to f(c)</m>. The sequence <m>(f(x_n))</m> lies in
          <m>T</m>, and because <m>g</m> is continuous at <m>f(c)</m>, it
          follows that
          <md>(g \circ f)(x_n)=g(f(x_n)) \to g(f(c))=(g \circ f)(c).</md>
          Therefore <m>g \circ f</m> is continuous at <m>c</m>.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </proposition>

    <corollary xml:id="cor-polynomials-and-rational-functions-continuous">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Every polynomial is continuous on <m>\R</m>, and every rational
          function is continuous on its domain.
        </p>
      </statement>

      <proof>
        <p>
          Constant functions and the identity function are continuous. By
          repeated application of the preceding proposition, finite sums and
          products of continuous functions are continuous, so every polynomial
          is continuous on <m>\R</m>. A rational function is a quotient
          <m>p/q</m> of two polynomials, and the quotient part of the same
          proposition shows that <m>p/q</m> is continuous at every point where
          <m>q \neq 0</m>.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </corollary>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="subsec-consequences-of-continuity">
    <title>Some Consequences</title>

    <p>
      Continuity does more than preserve limits under algebraic operations. It
      also imposes rigidity: a continuous function is determined by its values
      on a dense subset, and a nonzero value at one point forces the function
      to keep the same sign nearby.
    </p>

    <proposition xml:id="prop-continuous-zero-on-dense-subset">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>S \subseteq \R</m>, let <m>D \subseteq S</m> be dense in
          <m>S</m>, and let <m>f \colon S \to \R</m> be continuous on
          <m>S</m>. If <m>f(x)=0</m> for every <m>x \in D</m>, then
          <m>f(x)=0</m> for every <m>x \in S</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>

      <proof>
        <p>
          Fix <m>c \in S</m>. Since <m>D</m> is dense in <m>S</m>, for each
          <m>n \in \N</m> we may choose <m>d_n \in D</m> such that
          <m>|d_n-c| \lt 1/n</m>. Then <m>d_n \to c</m>. Because <m>f</m> is
          continuous at <m>c</m>, the sequential characterization gives
          <m>f(d_n) \to f(c)</m>. But every <m>d_n</m> lies in <m>D</m>, so
          <m>f(d_n)=0</m> for all <m>n</m>. Hence the constant sequence
          <m>(f(d_n))</m> converges to <m>0</m>, and therefore
          <m>f(c)=0</m>. Since <m>c</m> was arbitrary, <m>f=0</m> on
          <m>S</m>.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </proposition>

    <corollary xml:id="cor-continuous-functions-agree-on-dense-subset">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>S \subseteq \R</m> and let <m>D \subseteq S</m> be dense in
          <m>S</m>. If <m>f,g \colon S \to \R</m> are continuous on <m>S</m>
          and <m>f(x)=g(x)</m> for every <m>x \in D</m>, then
          <m>f=g</m> on <m>S</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>

      <proof>
        <p>
          The function <m>f-g</m> is continuous on <m>S</m> and vanishes on
          <m>D</m>. By the proposition, <m>f-g=0</m> on <m>S</m>. Therefore
          <m>f=g</m> on <m>S</m>.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </corollary>

    <proposition xml:id="prop-sign-preserved-near-nonzero-point">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>S \subseteq \R</m>, let <m>f \colon S \to \R</m>, and let
          <m>c \in S</m>. If <m>f</m> is continuous at <m>c</m> and
          <m>f(c) \neq 0</m>, then there exists <m>\delta \gt 0</m> such that
          <m>f(x)</m> has the same sign as <m>f(c)</m> whenever
          <m>x \in S</m> and <m>|x-c| \lt \delta</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>

      <proof>
        <p>
          Let <m>\varepsilon = |f(c)|/2</m>. Since <m>f</m> is continuous at
          <m>c</m>, there exists <m>\delta \gt 0</m> such that
          <md>|f(x)-f(c)| \lt \frac{|f(c)|}{2}</md>
          whenever <m>x \in S</m> and <m>|x-c| \lt \delta</m>. If
          <m>f(c) \gt 0</m>, then
          <md>f(x) \gt f(c)-\frac{|f(c)|}{2}=\frac{f(c)}{2}\gt 0.</md>
          If <m>f(c) \lt 0</m>, then
          <md>f(x) \lt f(c)+\frac{|f(c)|}{2}=\frac{f(c)}{2}\lt 0.</md>
          In either case, <m>f(x)</m> has the same sign as <m>f(c)</m>.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </proposition>
  </subsection>
</section>
